=== The Concept of Humanity and Communality === In European thought, distinctions such as that between {{ill|citizen|de|Bürger|ja|市民|zh|市民|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|barbarian|de|Barbar|ja|野蛮人|zh|野蛮人|lt=barbarian|lt_ja=蛮人|lt_de=Barbar|lt_zh=野蛮人|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and between {{ill|Christian|de|Christen|ja|キリスト教徒|zh|基督徒|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|pagan|de|Heiden|ja|異教徒|zh|异教徒|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, were fundamental; however, with the advent of the {{ill|Age of Enlightenment|de|Aufklärung|ja|啓蒙時代|zh|启蒙时代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a concept of “humanity” emerged that transcended these discriminations, and the history of humanity began to be presented as a history of progress through the self-completion of human beings. In this context, the concept of humanity came to be strongly associated with a communality that was to be realized<ref name="philo_sakagami" />.
=== Humanity as a Biological Species === As a biological species, “humanity” is a collective term encompassing all entities included in the concept of {{ill|human|de|Mensch|ja|ヒト|zh|人类|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, whether they are extant species (those still living) or fossil species (those that exist only as fossils)<ref name="britan">{{ill|Encyclopædia Britannica|de|Enzyklopädie Britannica|ja|ブリタニカ百科事典|zh|大英百科全书|qq=draft|qq=draft}} [Humanity]</ref>; however, there is considerable debate regarding the scope of this inclusion, and even fossil species other than {{ill|Homo sapiens|de|Homo sapiens|ja|ホモ・サピエンス|zh|智人|qq=draft|qq=draft}} continue to be the subject of ongoing discussion<ref name="britan" />. Common characteristics include the ability to {{ill|bipedalism|de|Bipedalismus|ja|直立歩行|zh|直立行走|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a reduction in the size of the {{ill|canine tooth|de|Eckzahn|ja|犬歯|zh|犬齿|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and the regression of the {{ill|tail|de|Schwanz|ja|尾|zh|尾巴|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, among others<ref name="britan" />.
