== Overview == Humanity refers to the concept of {{ill|human|de|Mensch|ja|人間|zh|人类|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/human|qq=}} as a kind that transcends the differences among individuals and {{ill|ethnic group|de|Volksgruppe|ja|民族|zh|民族|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ethnic group|qq=}}, that is, as a type of {{ill|kind|de|Gattung|ja|類|zh|类|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kind|qq=}} of human.
Theories concerning humanity in Western thought have undergone various transformations and debates over time, with significant theories including, for example, the monogenic theory, the polygenic theory, and the concept of humanity<ref name="philo_sakagami" />.
=== Monogenic and Polygenic Theories === (Although the {{ill|European world|de|Europäische Welt|ja|ヨーロッパ世界|zh|欧洲世界|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/European world|qq=}} was a {{ill|world|de|Welt|ja|世界|zh|世界|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/world|qq=}} of {{ill|Christianity|de|Christentum|ja|キリスト教|zh|基督教|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Christianity|qq=}}, in the Christian world the monogenic theory—which holds that all humanity are descendants of {{ill|Adam|de|Adam|ja|アダム|zh|亚当|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Adam|qq=}}—and the view of humans as bearing the image of God continued to hold persuasive power<ref name="philo_sakagami" />. However, as Europe entered the {{ill|Age of Discovery|de|Zeitalter der Entdeckungen|ja|大航海時代|zh|大航海时代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Age of Discovery|qq=}} and came into contact with people beyond its borders—with the accompanying influx of information—the question of how to regard those who appeared as “variants of human” or as {{ill|race|de|Rasse|ja|人種|zh|种族|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/race|qq=}} emerged as a major issue among Westerners<ref name="philo_sakagami" />. Regarding these issues, {{ill|Georges-Louis Leclerc de Buffon|de|Georges-Louis Leclerc de Buffon|ja|ジョルジュ＝ルイ・ルクレール・ド・ビュフォン|zh|乔治·路易·勒克莱尔·德·布丰|lt=Buffon|lt_ja=ビュフォン|lt_de=Buffon|lt_zh=布丰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Georges-Louis Leclerc de Buffon|qq=}} and many others adopted the monogenic theory, arguing that differences among human groups arose from differences in {{ill|climate|de|Klima|ja|風土|zh|风土|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/climate|qq=}}, {{ill|diet|de|Ernährung|ja|食物|zh|食物|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/diet|qq=}}, and {{ill|customs|de|Sitten|ja|習俗|zh|习俗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/customs|qq=}}, thereby asserting that humanity is a single species; in contrast, {{ill|Voltaire|de|Voltaire|ja|ヴォルテール|zh|伏尔泰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Voltaire|qq=}} argued for the polygenic theory<ref name="philo_sakagami" />. The conflict between the monogenic and polygenic theories persisted into the {{ill|19th century|de|19. Jahrhundert|ja|19世紀|zh|19世纪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/19th century|qq=}}, and in {{ill|1859|de|1859|ja|1859年|zh|1859年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1859|qq=}}, {{ill|Pierre Paul Broca|de|Pierre Paul Broca|ja|ピエール・ポール・ブローカ|zh|皮埃尔·保罗·布罗卡|lt=Broca|lt_ja=ブローカ|lt_de=Broca|lt_zh=布罗卡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Pierre Paul Broca|qq=}}, who founded the Paris Anthropological Society, also addressed these issues—stating that the differences between races are greater than those between animal {{ill|species|de|Art|ja|種 (分類学)|zh|种 (分类学)|lt=species|lt_ja=種 (分類学)|lt_de=Art|lt_zh=种|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/species|qq=}}<ref name="philo_sakagami" />.
Subsequently, concepts such as {{ill|social Darwinism|de|Sozialdarwinismus|ja|社会ダーウィニズム|zh|社会达尔文主义|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/social Darwinism|qq=}}, which posited that “evolved races dominate primitive ones,” emerged, and such ideas came to be conveniently exploited by {{ill|imperialism|de|Imperialismus|ja|帝国主義|zh|帝国主义|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/imperialism|qq=}}<ref name="philo_sakagami" />.
=== The Concept of Humanity and Communality === In European thought, distinctions such as that between {{ill|citizen|de|Bürger|ja|市民|zh|市民|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/citizen|qq=}} and {{ill|barbarian|de|Barbar|ja|野蛮人|zh|野蛮人|lt=barbarian|lt_ja=蛮人|lt_de=Barbar|lt_zh=野蛮人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/barbarian|qq=}}, and between {{ill|Christian|de|Christen|ja|キリスト教徒|zh|基督徒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Christian|qq=}} and {{ill|pagan|de|Heiden|ja|異教徒|zh|异教徒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pagan|qq=}}, were fundamental; however, with the advent of the {{ill|Age of Enlightenment|de|Aufklärung|ja|啓蒙時代|zh|启蒙时代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Age of Enlightenment|qq=}}, a concept of “humanity” emerged that transcended these discriminations, and the history of humanity began to be presented as a history of progress through the self-completion of human beings. In this context, the concept of humanity came to be strongly associated with a communality that was to be realized<ref name="philo_sakagami" />.
=== Humanity as a Biological Species === As a biological species, “humanity” is a collective term encompassing all entities included in the concept of {{ill|human|de|Mensch|ja|ヒト|zh|人类|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/human|qq=}}, whether they are extant species (those still living) or fossil species (those that exist only as fossils)<ref name="britan">{{ill|Encyclopædia Britannica|de|Enzyklopädie Britannica|ja|ブリタニカ百科事典|zh|大英百科全书|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Encyclopædia Britannica|qq=}} [Humanity]</ref>; however, there is considerable debate regarding the scope of this inclusion, and even fossil species other than {{ill|Homo sapiens|de|Homo sapiens|ja|ホモ・サピエンス|zh|智人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Homo sapiens|qq=}} continue to be the subject of ongoing discussion<ref name="britan" />. Common characteristics include the ability to {{ill|bipedalism|de|Bipedalismus|ja|直立歩行|zh|直立行走|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bipedalism|qq=}}, a reduction in the size of the {{ill|canine tooth|de|Eckzahn|ja|犬歯|zh|犬齿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/canine tooth|qq=}}, and the regression of the {{ill|tail|de|Schwanz|ja|尾|zh|尾巴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tail|qq=}}, among others<ref name="britan" />.
