=== Monogenic and Polygenic Theories === (Although the {{ill|European world|de|Europäische Welt|ja|ヨーロッパ世界|zh|欧洲世界|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/European world|qq=}} was a [[:en:World|world]] of [[:en:Christianity|Christianity]], in the Christian world the monogenic theory—which holds that all humanity are descendants of [[:en:Adam|Adam]]—and the view of humans as bearing the image of God continued to hold persuasive power<ref name="philo_sakagami" />. However, as Europe entered the [[:en:Age of Discovery|Age of Discovery]] and came into contact with people beyond its borders—with the accompanying influx of information—the question of how to regard those who appeared as “variants of human” or as [[:en:Race (human categorization)|race]] emerged as a major issue among Westerners<ref name="philo_sakagami" />. Regarding these issues, [[:en:Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon|Buffon]] and many others adopted the monogenic theory, arguing that differences among human groups arose from differences in [[:en:Climate|climate]], [[:en:Nutrition|diet]], and [[:en:Sion, Switzerland|customs]], thereby asserting that humanity is a single species; in contrast, [[:en:Voltaire|Voltaire]] argued for the polygenic theory<ref name="philo_sakagami" />. The conflict between the monogenic and polygenic theories persisted into the [[:en:19th century|19th century]], and in [[:en:1859|1859]], [[:en:Paul Broca|Broca]], who founded the Paris Anthropological Society, also addressed these issues—stating that the differences between races are greater than those between animal [[:en:Species|species]]<ref name="philo_sakagami" />.
Subsequently, concepts such as [[:en:Social Darwinism|social Darwinism]], which posited that “evolved races dominate primitive ones,” emerged, and such ideas came to be conveniently exploited by [[:en:Imperialism|imperialism]]<ref name="philo_sakagami" />.
=== The Concept of Humanity and Communality === In European thought, distinctions such as that between [[:en:Citizenship|citizen]] and [[:en:Barbarian|barbarian]], and between [[:en:Christians|Christian]] and [[:en:Heiden|pagan]], were fundamental; however, with the advent of the [[:en:Age of Enlightenment|Age of Enlightenment]], a concept of “humanity” emerged that transcended these discriminations, and the history of humanity began to be presented as a history of progress through the self-completion of human beings. In this context, the concept of humanity came to be strongly associated with a communality that was to be realized<ref name="philo_sakagami" />.
=== Humanity as a Biological Species === As a biological species, “humanity” is a collective term encompassing all entities included in the concept of [[:en:Human|human]], whether they are extant species (those still living) or fossil species (those that exist only as fossils)<ref name="britan">[[:en:Encyclopædia Britannica|Encyclopædia Britannica]] [Humanity]</ref>; however, there is considerable debate regarding the scope of this inclusion, and even fossil species other than {{ill|Homo sapiens|de|Homo sapiens|ja|ホモ・サピエンス|zh|智人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Homo sapiens|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} continue to be the subject of ongoing discussion<ref name="britan" />. Common characteristics include the ability to {{ill|bipedalism|de|Bipedalismus|ja|直立歩行|zh|直立行走|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bipedalism|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 直立二足歩行}}, a reduction in the size of the [[:en:Canine tooth|canine tooth]], and the regression of the [[:en:Tail|tail]], among others<ref name="britan" />.
